WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.320
Okay, so NPR's Planet Money did an episode about a month ago on some of the problems with how

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:13.360
residential solar companies operate. And there's this excerpt about a couple who had signed a 20

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:17.840
year lease on solar panels, and it says that they had used about half as much electricity

00:00:17.840 --> 00:00:22.480
from their power company as the previous year. And at first, this sounds pretty good until you

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:26.160
realize that the solar company had promised these new panels to replace all of their power.

00:00:26.879 --> 00:00:32.560
So this represents clearly a poor prediction in terms of how much energy was going to be

00:00:33.119 --> 00:00:36.720
consumed or how much energy was going to be produced by the panels. But it's not

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:41.119
just bad because it's inaccurate. It's also bad because the solar company hadn't provided

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:45.680
any notion of the range of potential outcomes that might come from installing these panels.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:49.680
They provided the couple with a very narrow picture about what would happen.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:53.520
And then when that wasn't met, the couple was, you know, reasonably upset.

00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:58.480
And this might seem like a somewhat contrived example, because you might just think,

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:02.160
okay, the solar company was intentionally misleading this couple. But I imagine a lot

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:05.919
of people in this room that have been in situations where they provided predictions

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:11.040
that maybe didn't have measures of uncertainty with them. And then the stakeholder that received

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:17.279
them was upset or surprised when things didn't go how those predictions had suggested they would.

00:01:17.919 --> 00:01:22.720
So today I'm going to be talking about some of those situations where it's really important to

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:27.760
provide measures of uncertainty. And I'll also be talking through a procedure that works pretty well

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:31.839
in regression context where you are predicting some continuous variable.

00:01:33.199 --> 00:01:38.400
Okay, so there are some situations where your predictions are going to lead directly to some

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:44.639
outcome. So you might picture something like spam filters, where they will sort the junk

00:01:44.639 --> 00:01:50.559
out of your inbox without any work on your part. But there are also many, many situations where

00:01:50.559 --> 00:01:55.199
your predictions are going to go to some intermediary agent. And that intermediary

00:01:55.199 --> 00:02:00.400
agent is going to ultimately make some decision. So maybe you're doing climate forecasts that are

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:06.400
going to be used in planning solar farms. Or maybe you are predicting transit ridership that's used

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:12.000
by a city planner in determining bus routes. Or maybe you're like me and you do forecasts on

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:17.440
sales figures that are then helpful in operations and planning. In each of these cases where your

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:22.160
model is providing information to some agents, it's often important to provide more than just a

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:27.199
prediction, but to give some additional context on that prediction that can be helpful in the greater

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:32.479
decision making for your stakeholders. Now there's lots of different types of information you might

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:38.080
provide. You might provide information about how appropriate is this model for the particular

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:43.199
observations you're looking at. Or you might provide information that gets at what is driving

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:47.520
the prediction that you're actually providing. What I'm going to be talking about today though

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:52.559
is measures of uncertainty. And I'm going to suggest that rather than providing a point

00:02:52.559 --> 00:02:57.919
estimate for your prediction, you often want to provide a range within which your prediction is

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:02.399
going to fall. So you want to provide a prediction interval. And this range of values is helpful

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:09.440
both in informing stakeholders, but it can also be helpful in informing what bounds you actually

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:13.679
want those stakeholders to operate within. So to illustrate this latter point, I'm going to talk

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:18.800
through a couple different models for pricing. So let's think about something like commodities.

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:24.800
Commodities are relatively simple products. You've got mature markets with reasonably full information.

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:29.199
So the price for a commodity at any given moment is typically going to fall within some

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:33.919
relatively narrow band. If we compare this to something like used cars where you have a really

00:03:33.919 --> 00:03:39.759
complicated product and potentially gaps in information or, you know, intense customizations

00:03:39.759 --> 00:03:44.320
associated with that product, the uncertainty in what an appropriate price is going to be a lot

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:50.160
greater. And this is part of why buying used cars is notoriously this exercise in haggling.

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:55.440
It's this greater uncertainty that gives greater agency to the downstream agent in coming to that

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:02.479
final price. But we also see that as models improve, as you get more information, the role of

00:04:02.479 --> 00:04:07.839
those intermediary agents can be reduced. So we see things like Carvana or other online platforms

00:04:07.839 --> 00:04:13.440
that lean more on their prediction and reduce the role of those intermediary agents. So my point with

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:19.359
this is just to say that measures of uncertainty are helpful both in informing stakeholders, but

00:04:19.359 --> 00:04:24.160
also can be helpful in defining the bounds within which we want those stakeholders to actually

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:30.079
operate. So up to now, I've just been showing prediction intervals at a single outcome. But in

00:04:30.079 --> 00:04:36.239
the context of predictive modeling, we often want to show prediction intervals across, you know, a

00:04:36.239 --> 00:04:43.040
range of potential inputs, right? And I want to talk briefly too about this confusion that often

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:47.839
happens in the context of prediction between confidence intervals and prediction intervals.

00:04:48.799 --> 00:04:52.000
This is just something that I feel like comes up almost every time I talk about prediction

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.079
intervals, so I just want to spend a little time talking about it. As people often confuse these two

00:04:56.079 --> 00:05:00.000
and will frequently output confidence intervals when what they mean to be doing

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.959
is outputting prediction intervals. So confidence intervals mostly come from uncertainty in fitting

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:12.720
the model. And they represent intervals related to the average across the entire population at

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:17.040
some point. And confidence intervals are really useful in contexts where you're evaluating

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:22.160
coefficients or doing other types of statistical tests. But in our context, we're more interested in

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:26.799
prediction intervals. Prediction intervals are driven by uncertainty in the sample and reflect

00:05:26.799 --> 00:05:32.239
the variability in individual outcomes. So just to kind of, like, iron, you know, knock

00:05:32.239 --> 00:05:36.559
this message home about the types of phrasing that is commonly used between these two types

00:05:36.559 --> 00:05:43.359
of intervals, if we think of this as a model of, let's say, baby weight by age, and we want to

00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:48.320
describe confidence intervals, you might have a statement like, we're 90% sure that the average

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:53.119
weight among all three-month-olds is between 12 and 12 and a half pounds. This is

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:57.600
kind of like a confidence interval-like statement. Whereas for prediction intervals, you'd say

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:02.480
something like, we're 90% sure that the weight of an individual three-month-old will be between 10

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:08.079
and 14 pounds. This first statement is about making global claims about the world. We're saying, what is

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:13.519
the average weight across all three-month-olds? Where the latter represents a measure of uncertainty

00:06:13.519 --> 00:06:18.799
on an individual observation. We're saying, what's an appropriate weight for some given three-month-old?

00:06:19.519 --> 00:06:24.000
And when we're outputting predictions, we generally care about these latter types of statements.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:31.040
So let's talk briefly about outputting predictions. Some types of models, like linear regression,

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:36.720
come set up to easily output prediction intervals already. In the predict function,

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:41.519
here I have this ellenfit object, which is just the model I already fit. And I'm giving it some

00:06:41.519 --> 00:06:46.079
new set of observations, and I'm saying that I want to output prediction intervals, and I want

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:52.720
them to be 90% prediction intervals. And what this is going to do, then, is output lower and upper

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:57.040
bounds for each of these observations that together constitute my prediction interval.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.480
I just want to make a note, too, that here I'm specifying predint. The default for a lot of

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:06.559
packages, if you don't specify the type there, is going to output constant rules, whereas, again,

00:07:06.559 --> 00:07:09.679
what you want in this context is often prediction intervals. So just be careful that you're actually

00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:15.679
outputting the right thing. When you're evaluating prediction intervals, it's often helpful to

00:07:16.239 --> 00:07:23.200
visualize them. So in this context, I've built a model on price. And here I have some new set

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:28.399
of observations that I'm producing prediction intervals on that the model never saw. Each of

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:34.399
those teal bands represents a prediction interval for some observation. And what the red point

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:40.320
represents is the outcome, is the actual outcome that occurred. And kind of like the baseline way

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:44.799
that we use for evaluating prediction intervals is in terms of coverage. So we can say that an

00:07:44.799 --> 00:07:50.799
individual observation is covered if the outcome actually fell within our prediction interval.

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:58.000
So in this case, if we are outputting 90% prediction intervals, that means that 90%

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.119
of the time, our outcome should actually fall within those bands. So this is kind of like the

00:08:03.119 --> 00:08:07.200
baseline measure that we want to use. We want to see, is our coverage rate actually what we're

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:12.959
expecting it to be? But we don't just care about coverage. We also care about the interval width.

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:18.320
Because if we have more narrow intervals, that means our model is doing a better job fitting

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:23.600
the data. And having less uncertainty in your predictions is going to be more useful for

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:27.600
whatever stakeholders you're sharing them with. So we have kind of this dual goal of

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:31.440
meeting our coverage requirements while also having as narrow intervals as possible.

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:38.320
But simple linear regression, the prediction rules that get outputted from this type of model

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:44.799
have a number of weaknesses that go with them. One is that there's no guarantee of coverage on

00:08:44.799 --> 00:08:51.200
out-of-sample data. So it's not necessarily the case that if we give a new set of observations

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:57.359
to our model, that those observations are going to fall within our bands at the rate with which we

00:08:57.359 --> 00:09:03.280
expect them to. Another weakness is that as we're trying to fit other types of models to try and

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:08.400
improve our fit, lots of these different model types don't actually output prediction intervals

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:12.159
by default. So we are somewhat constrained in terms of the types of fits we can build.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.280
And then also, these types of prediction rules from simple linear regression come with a lot

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:25.039
of assumptions. A big one is that they assume constant variance across observations. But if

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:30.719
we think back to the example with used cars, you might think that a car that has 10,000 miles on

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:35.280
it is going to have a lot less uncertainty in terms of what the potential price range is compared

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:38.799
to a car with 100,000 miles on it that may have a lot more uncertainty in terms of what the

00:09:38.799 --> 00:09:47.200
eventual price is. So what we want then is some type of model and procedure that is going to

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:51.760
give us some guarantees around coverage. It's going to be relatively model agnostic so we can

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:55.840
use different types of fitting procedures. And it's going to be assumption-free, or at least

00:09:55.840 --> 00:10:01.440
mostly assumption-free. So these are kind of like what we want in our procedure for producing

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:06.719
prediction intervals. And to achieve these, we're going to turn to this field called conformal

00:10:06.719 --> 00:10:12.320
prediction. And this is a field of study that's committed to producing good measures of uncertainty

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:18.559
with minimal observations. And I'll just say that conformal prediction is very popular right now.

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:23.520
There's lots of different procedures you can use. And it can be used also in classification contexts

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:30.320
and different types of problem spaces. But today, I'm going to be talking about it for regression

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:35.520
contexts where we're predicting some kind of continuous variable. And in this case, I'm going

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:40.080
to be talking through a procedure called conformalized quantile regression that is a good heuristic to

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:49.919
use in these situations. And the two main steps of this procedure is essentially to first fit lower

00:10:49.919 --> 00:10:55.760
and upper bounds, and then to adjust those bounds using calibration data. So to talk through this

00:10:55.760 --> 00:11:00.320
in a little bit more detail, I'm first just going to talk about kind of the more traditional approach

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:03.840
for producing prediction intervals using, you know, the simple linear regression method I was talking

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.719
about before. So kind of the classical approach for producing prediction intervals is you'll start

00:11:08.719 --> 00:11:14.479
with some model that was fit on the expected value. Then to get your prediction intervals, what

00:11:14.479 --> 00:11:19.039
you're actually doing is you're just taking that expected value, and to get your upper bound, you're

00:11:19.039 --> 00:11:24.159
adding some measure related to the average error. And then to get the lower bound, you're taking

00:11:24.159 --> 00:11:28.640
that kind of like average error measure and subtracting it from your expected value. So, you

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:35.359
know, the expected value plus or minus these kind of average error measures give you that interval.

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:42.239
This is different from the procedure that you follow when using quantile regression. So in

00:11:42.239 --> 00:11:48.159
quantile regression, you don't actually even need the model fit based off of expected value. What

00:11:48.159 --> 00:11:55.119
you're doing is you're fitting models directly on those lower and upper bounds. So let's say we want

00:11:55.119 --> 00:11:59.440
prediction intervals that are 80% prediction intervals. In this case, our lower bound is a

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:04.000
model that's actually being fit to the 10th percentile data, and our upper bound is the

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:09.440
models we fit to the 90th percentile data. So in this case, rather than saying, okay, give me a

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:13.359
model for the expected value, we're saying give me two models, one for my lower bound and one for my

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:20.239
upper bound, and I'm just directly predicting those bounds. This offers some advantages here

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:25.440
because it gives a little more flexibility. As you can see in this case, we're no longer constrained

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:32.400
to having kind of constant variance across our inputs. That's one area of flexibility. Also,

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:38.000
you can fit lots of different models that are able to be trained based off of this quantile

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.159
output. So this kind of opens up the types of models you can use as well. So you kind of get

00:12:42.159 --> 00:12:49.039
this ability to fit the quantiles expands what you can actually do in terms of how adaptive

00:12:49.039 --> 00:12:53.919
your prediction intervals can be. So that's the first step, is you just start basically training

00:12:53.919 --> 00:13:02.239
based off the lower bound and the upper bound. The next step is to just pass in some out-of-sample

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:07.760
data that you're going to use to calibrate these bounds. So it's common that your initial bounds

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:12.960
may be a little bit too narrow. So I pass in this next set of data. It's going to let you calibrate

00:13:14.479 --> 00:13:19.119
some adjustment on those bounds. So here, we'll take each of these observations on our

00:13:19.119 --> 00:13:23.679
calibration data set, and we'll score them based off of if they're covered and their distance from

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:30.000
the nearest bound. And then if we're fitting an 80% prediction interval, we'll take the outcome

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
that falls at the 80th percentile in terms of distance from the nearest bound, and then we'll

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:39.440
use that score as a concept to move the upper and lower bounds to expand the upper and lower bounds.

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:47.039
And now we have these conformalized quantiles that have our coverage

00:13:47.039 --> 00:13:51.919
guarantees. So now we have a flexible, adaptive approach that also has these coverage guarantees

00:13:51.919 --> 00:13:58.880
that we want. In terms of implementations of this approach, NR, the probability package,

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:03.520
has a bunch of really useful tools for doing conformal inference. Max Kuhn gave a talk on this

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:07.919
last year that I really recommend checking out. In terms of this conformalized quantile regression

00:14:08.559 --> 00:14:13.119
method, there's this function int conformal quantile that is an implementation of this

00:14:13.119 --> 00:14:19.359
with random forests. In Python, you can use the maybe package. And then I also really recommend

00:14:19.359 --> 00:14:24.559
checking out the article as well as associated YouTube videos on a general introduction to

00:14:24.559 --> 00:14:28.239
conformal prediction if you want to get a little bit more detail on these procedures and also

00:14:28.239 --> 00:14:33.520
where you can use them in different contexts. So my hope is that you continue to develop your

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:37.599
tool set and ability to share measures of uncertainty when when sharing predictions

00:14:37.599 --> 00:14:39.119
with stakeholders. Thank you.

00:14:48.479 --> 00:14:55.440
Thank you very much. So again, questions on Slido, please. So we're going to have you

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:59.919
unplug so the next person can. And then we're going to move over for our Q&A.

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:09.440
Tomasz is coming. That is good. Thank you very much. So how would conformal prediction work

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:14.640
or would it work well on count data and other distributions with strict boundaries?

00:15:15.919 --> 00:15:21.840
So I haven't done, I haven't used conformal prediction a lot in the context of count data.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:27.760
I will say that like the big assumption that conformal prediction has is there's still this

00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:32.880
exchangeability assumption. So essentially just that your data is, it's similar to that your

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:37.599
data's IID. That's kind of the biggest option is you don't have to look out for. But I haven't

00:15:37.599 --> 00:15:41.520
done anything with, I haven't used it for count data. So I don't want to comment exactly and

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:48.400
where it fits in there. Okay. You just mentioned data. We also have a question on this.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:55.359
What are you using as the calibration data set? Are you splitting the data and using it like

00:15:55.359 --> 00:16:01.280
train and test data or how does it? It's basically in this context, for the example I gave, you just

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:05.440
have another holdout data set that you essentially use for calibration. So picture your train,

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:09.520
your calibration data, and then your test data. So it's just like an additional calibration data

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:16.320
set. There's another approach to conformal prediction where you don't need to have this

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:20.239
separate calibration data set, but that procedure takes a lot longer. But if you want to look into,

00:16:20.239 --> 00:16:25.599
it's called full conformal inference or it's sometimes called transductive conformal inference.

00:16:25.599 --> 00:16:30.080
So if you want to like search those terms and that's a different procedure. But here I'm just

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:34.719
using this like split conformal procedure, which is kind of the most common. It's the fastest and

00:16:34.719 --> 00:16:40.000
it's kind of the easiest to set up. Okay. Somebody wants to see the last slide again,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.840
but I'm going to make you shout out your link because I think we've switched screens.

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:53.440
Yeah. So just go to my, if you just go to GitHub and then Burr Shallow is B-R-S-H-A-L-L-O.

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:57.280
That's my user. And then Posit-2024. I have the slides up there.

00:16:57.280 --> 00:17:00.880
Okay. There's slightly, I'm going to upload a new set of slides there. This is

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:04.000
made some last minute changes, but. They're looking for the resources. They will.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:11.040
The resources will be there. Yes. Okay. What kind of guarantee is the coverage guarantee?

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.800
So the coverage guarantee is essentially just that if you say, okay, I want, you know,

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:21.119
90% prediction intervals to actually have coverage rates that are 90%. That's, that's

00:17:21.119 --> 00:17:26.640
what the guarantee is. In, in terms of, I think the question might be asking, there's this notion

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:31.920
of marginal coverage versus conditional coverage. Marginal coverage basically just means that you

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:39.040
have the 90% is across your data sets. But it's not necessarily local to each region. So some

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:42.560
areas you might have like 95% coverage, other places you might have like 85% coverage,

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:46.719
but it's going to vary. Conditional coverage is basically that you have this coverage rate

00:17:46.719 --> 00:17:50.000
more consistently across your dataset. The coverage guarantee from conformalized

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:56.000
quantile regression is just as a marginal guarantee, but it tends to actually have

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:01.040
decent conditional coverage because the quantile regression procedure has that flexibility built

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:04.000
in. So it's like only as the guarantee for marginal coverage, but it usually works pretty

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.319
well in terms of getting decent conditional coverage as well.

00:18:07.439 --> 00:18:19.280
Thank you. So we're basically at time. So please give up a hand for Brian.

